        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Brown, build, and braise",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the {{vegetable-oil}} in a wide pan over high heat. Season the {{chicken-thigh}} with {{sea-salt-fine}} and {{black-pepper}}. Brown skin-side down for 4 minutes until golden. Transfer to the slow cooker. Add the {{onion}} to the pan and fry for 2 minutes. Add the {{garlic}} and {{tomato-puree}} and cook for 1 minute. Pour in the {{red-wine}} and let it bubble briefly. Pour over the chicken. Add the {{tinned-tomatoes}}, {{olives-black}}, {{oregano-dried}}, and {{bay-leaves}}. Cook on low for 6 to 8 hours, until the chicken is tender and the sauce is thick. Remove the {{bay-leaves}} before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "items": [
            {
              "fix": "Always let the wine bubble for at least 1 minute in the pan before adding it to the slow cooker. This cooks off the sharpest alcohol",
              "cause": "Red wine not allowed to bubble off before going in",
              "symptom": "Sauce bitter and wine-sharp"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Rinse brine-packed olives in cold water before adding. Oil-packed olives can go in as they are",
              "cause": "Olives in brine rather than in oil",
              "symptom": "Olives taste overwhelmingly salty"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid for the last 30 minutes on high to reduce. The sauce should be thick enough to coat a spoon",
              "cause": "Too much liquid added, or lid not sealing",
              "symptom": "Sauce too thin"
            }
          ]
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Chicken cacciatore is a weeknight Italian braise that suits the slow cooker completely. The olives and tomatoes produce enough liquid to braise the chicken without adding stock. Serve with pasta or polenta, and spoon the sauce generously. A green salad alongside cuts through the richness.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
